(Ford GoBike Exploration)¶

by (Buthaina Alotaibi)¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

The dataset for Ford GoBike aggregates the data for rides in February 2019, Ford GoBike is the Bay Areas bike share system. Bay Area Bike Share was introduced in 2013. It services San Francisco, the East Bay and San Jose. It contains 183412 row and 16 columns.

In [2]:
# import all packages and set plots to be embedded inline

In [3]:
#Loading the dataset
df = pd.read_csv('201902-fordgobike-tripdata.csv')

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

  • duration_sec int64: Trip Duration (seconds)
  • start_time object: Start Time and Date
  • end_time object: End Time and Date
  • start_station_id float64: Start Station ID
  • start_station_name object: Start Station Name
  • start_station_latitude float64: Start Station Latitude
  • start_station_longitude float64: Start Station Longitude
  • end_station_id float64: End Station ID
  • end_station_name object: End Station Name
  • end_station_latitude float64: End Station Latitude
  • end_station_longitude float64: End Station Longitude
  • bike_id int64: Bike ID
  • user_type object: User Type (Subscriber or Customer Subscriber = Member or Customer = --Casual)
  • member_birth_year float64: Member Year of Birth
  • member_gender object: Member Gender
  • bike_share_for_all_trip object: Boolean to track members who are enrolled in the "Bike Share for All" program for low-income residents

The main feature of interest for me is the duration and find what other features affect the duration. Also, Im interested to find what are the most visited stations and the characteristics of the visitors.

I believe that most of the features can help me and support my investigation but specially start_time, end_time and member_birth_year.

Cleaning¶

In [12]:
df_clean = df.copy()
In [13]:
#Drop missing values
df_clean.dropna(inplace=True)
In [14]:
#Change ID columns type to object
df_clean['bike_id'] = df_clean['bike_id'].astype('object')
df_clean['end_station_id'] = df_clean['end_station_id'].astype('object')
df_clean['start_station_id'] = df_clean['start_station_id'].astype('object')
In [15]:
#Change date/time columns to date/time type
df_clean['start_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_clean['start_time'])
df_clean['end_time'] = pd.to_datetime(df_clean['end_time'])

Feature engineering¶

In [16]:
#Create new feature to specify months
df_clean['start_month_num'] = df_clean['start_time'].apply(lambda time: time.month)
df_clean['start_month_char'] = df_clean['start_month_num'].apply(lambda x: calendar.month_abbr[x])
In [17]:
#Create new feature to specify weekdays
df_clean['start_weekday_num'] = df_clean['start_time'].apply(lambda time: time.dayofweek)
dmap = {0:'Mon',1:'Tue',2:'Wed',3:'Thu',4:'Fri',5:'Sat',6:'Sun'}
df_clean['start_weekday_char'] = df_clean['start_weekday_num'].map(dmap)

The plot shows the distribution between weekdays. The distribution between weekdays shows that Thursday and Tuesday are the peak days and most of the rides are during these days, on the other hand Sunday and Saturday are the least days. We can conclude from this information that most of the members are using it for work so theres no need to use it on the weekends.

This plot shows the distribution for start stations each day, the weekend has the least traffic. There is no big difference between the stations during the days of the week, most of the rides are during Thursday and Tuesday in all stations, the least are on Saturday and Sunday.

Multivariate Exploration¶

In [41]:
cat_markers = [['Customer', 's'],
               ['Subscriber', '^']]
plt.figure(figsize=[ 11.69, 8.27])
for cat, marker in cat_markers:
    df_cat = df_clean[df_clean['user_type'] == cat]
    plt.scatter(data = df_cat, x = 'member_age', y = 'duration_sec', marker = marker, alpha = .5);
plt.legend(['Customer', 'Subscriber']);
plt.xlim(df_clean['member_age'].min(), 100);
plt.title('Comparing Ride Duration Across Ages and Genders', fontsize = 18);
plt.xlabel('Ages');
plt.ylabel('Number of Rides');
plt.style.use('seaborn')

This plot compares the duration of rides across ages and user types. The subscriber type tends to overlap in small durations and the customer type has more durations. Most of the two types are between 20-60 years.
